T1  - THE FULL RECESSION: PRIVATE VERSUS SOCIAL COSTS OF COVID-19
AU  - Cordoba, Juan-Carlos
AU  - Ripoll, Marla
AU  - Yang, Siqiang
Y1  - 2024/02/01
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12667
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 547
EP  - 582
VL  - 65
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12667
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract 2020 official recession figures ignore the costs associated with the loss of human life due to COVID-19. This article constructs full recession measures that consider the death toll. Our model features nonexpected utility, leisure, age-specific survival rates, and tractable heterogeneity. We find an average full recession of 10.7%, which reflects the net value of an aggregate drop in consumption of 2.7%, an average increase of 197 leisure hours and about 540,000 lives lost in the first pandemic year. The full recession for a utilitarian planner is 14.5%, which aligns with that of individuals in their late 50s.
ER  - 

